#1 Intramucosal adenocarcinoma of the rectum
Ms. Hogan does have evidence of a mass lesion at approximately 15-cm from the anal verge which is near the boundary of where we would consider it rectal versus sigmoid in location.  As of this time, we have no evidence of invasive adenocarcinoma, although there is certainly evidence of intramucosal adenocarcinoma.  Given the size of the mass, we do have concern that it may well be invasive.  However, without this knowledge and complete staging, it is very difficult to make recommendations regarding the best plan of care at this time.  I am reassured that there is no evidence of distant metastatic disease on the CT-scan or chest x-ray performed today.
To obtain more complete staging, I have discussed with Dr. Depriest the potentiality of having her undergo a flexible sigmoidoscopy, and depending on what is seen on this study, perhaps a transrectal ultrasound to complete staging.  He is in agreement with this plan and also raises the possibility of potential endoscopic removal of this lesion, at which time further pathology could be performed and staging completed.  Dr. Depriest will see Ms. Hogan later this afternoon and make his recommendations at that time.  We will also obtain a CT-scan of the chest to ensure no distant metastatic disease in that location.
This was discussed at length with Ms. Hogan who asked multiple informed questions that were answered this afternoon.
I have discussed this patient at length with Dr. Herring who has seen and examined the patient.  Please see her supervisory note for further details.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at Ankeny County Memorial Hospital.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

