[start section id="20103"]

Ms. Hogan is a very pleasant 49-year-old female who was in her usual state of health until July of this year when she underwent screening colonoscopy.  She states that prior to this, she had no GI symptoms, frankly denying anorexia, nausea, vomiting, weight-loss, diarrhea, constipation, blood in the stool, or change in stool caliber.  During this procedure on July 16, 2010, a 5- to 6-cm mass was noted approximately 15-cm from the anal verge.  This was concerning for malignancy, and thus multiple biopsies were taken.  Pathology review of this specimen revealed intramucosal adenocarcinoma in association with high-grade dysplasia.  There was no evidence of invasive disease noted.  Given this finding, Ms. Hogan was referred to Wilber Care Center of Pipestone for further evaluation and recommendations.
On further review of her history, Ms. Hogan does report an episode in March of 2010 where she had some right lower quadrant pain that was clinically consistent with appendicitis.  CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis, right upper quadrant ultrasound, and a pelvic ultrasound revealed only an echogenic liver, a right ovarian cyst that was unchanged from prior examination, and no obvious cause for this pain.  It resolved spontaneously after one-week, and she has been without the pain since.
Ms. Hogan states that she continues to be asymptomatic, denying all the gastrointestinal symptoms as above as well as fevers, chills, chest pain, shortness-of-breath, headache, visual changes, or focal neurologic symptom.  Her ECOG performance status is 0.

